module.exports = [
  [157, "The Psychology of Decision Making", "心理", 2, "Every day, people make thousands of decisions, from trivial choices about what to eat to consequential decisions about careers and relationships. Understanding how we make decisions and the biases that influence our choices has been a central focus of psychological research.\n\nDaniel Kahneman's work, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Economics, identified two systems of thinking. System 1 operates automatically and quickly with little effort, relying on intuition and emotion. System 2 involves deliberate, effortful thinking that requires concentration. Most daily decisions rely on System 1, which is efficient but prone to systematic errors known as cognitive biases.\n\nConfirmation bias leads people to seek information that confirms their existing beliefs while ignoring contradictory evidence. The anchoring effect causes people to rely too heavily on the first piece of information they encounter when making decisions. Loss aversion means that people feel the pain of losing something more intensely than the pleasure of gaining something equivalent. The availability heuristic leads people to judge the likelihood of events based on how easily examples come to mind rather than actual probability.\n\nUnderstanding these biases can improve decision-making. Taking time to engage System 2 thinking for important decisions, seeking diverse perspectives, considering alternative explanations, and being aware of emotional influences all contribute to better choices. Organizations can implement structured decision-making processes that reduce the impact of individual biases.",
  "人们每天做出数千个决定，从吃什么的小选择到关于职业和关系的重大决定。理解我们如何做出决定以及影响我们选择的偏见一直是心理学研究的核心焦点。\n\n丹尼尔·卡尼曼的工作确定了两套思维系统。系统1自动快速运作，依赖直觉和情感。系统2涉及深思熟虑的思维。大多数日常决定依赖系统1，它高效但容易出现系统性错误，即认知偏差。\n\n确认偏差导致人们寻找确认现有信念的信息。锚定效应使人们过于依赖遇到的第一条信息。损失厌恶意味着人们感受失去的痛苦比获得同等东西的快乐更强烈。可得性启发使人们根据例子容易回忆的程度而非实际概率来判断事件可能性。\n\n理解这些偏见可以改善决策。花时间对重要决定使用系统2思维、寻求多元观点和考虑替代解释都有助于做出更好的选择。",
  332, [["What is System 1 thinking?","Deliberate and effortful thinking","Automatic, quick thinking relying on intuition and emotion","Mathematical calculation","Group discussion","B","文章指出系统1自动快速运作，依赖直觉和情感。"],["What does confirmation bias cause people to do?","Consider all evidence equally","Seek information confirming existing beliefs while ignoring contradictory evidence","Make decisions based on emotions only","Always choose the safest option","B","文章指出确认偏差导致人们寻找确认现有信念的信息而忽略矛盾证据。"],["What does loss aversion mean?","People prefer losing to gaining","People feel the pain of losing more intensely than the pleasure of gaining something equivalent","People always avoid risky decisions","People never experience regret","B","文章指出损失厌恶意味着人们感受失去的痛苦比获得同等东西的快乐更强烈。"],["The word 'heuristic' most likely means:","A mathematical proof","A mental shortcut or rule of thumb used for quick judgments","A detailed analysis","A scientific law","B","'heuristic'意为'启发式'，即用于快速判断的心理捷径或经验法则。"]]],
  [158, "Childhood Development and Attachment", "心理", 1, "Attachment theory, developed by John Bowlby and Mary Ainsworth, describes how the emotional bonds formed between children and their caregivers shape psychological development throughout life. These early relationships create internal working models that influence how individuals approach relationships well into adulthood.\n\nAinsworth identified three primary attachment styles through her Strange Situation experiments. Securely attached children explore confidently when their caregiver is present, become distressed when separated, and are comforted upon reunion. Anxiously attached children are reluctant to explore, become extremely distressed by separation, and are difficult to comfort upon reunion. Avoidantly attached children show little distress upon separation and avoid contact upon reunion.\n\nAttachment styles formed in childhood tend to persist into adult relationships. Securely attached adults form healthy, trusting relationships. Anxiously attached adults may be clingy, jealous, and fear abandonment. Avoidantly attached adults may struggle with emotional intimacy and prefer independence. However, attachment styles are not deterministic; experiences in later relationships can modify internal working models.\n\nSecure attachment develops when caregivers consistently respond to children's needs with sensitivity and warmth. Factors that compromise secure attachment include parental mental health problems, substance abuse, domestic violence, and severe economic stress. Early intervention programs that support sensitive caregiving can promote secure attachment, potentially preventing a cascade of developmental difficulties.",
  "依恋理论由约翰·鲍尔比和玛丽·安斯沃思发展，描述了儿童和照顾者之间形成的情感纽带如何塑造终身的心理发展。这些早期关系创造了内在工作模型，影响个体如何处理成年后的关系。\n\n安斯沃思通过陌生情境实验确定了三种主要依恋风格。安全型依恋的儿童在照顾者在场时自信地探索。焦虑型依恋的儿童不愿探索，对分离极度不安。回避型依恋的儿童对分离很少表现出不安，重聚时避免接触。\n\n童年形成的依恋风格往往会持续到成年关系中。安全型依恋的成年人形成健康、信任的关系。然而依恋风格不是决定性的；后期关系中的经验可以修改内在工作模型。\n\n当照顾者始终如一地以敏感和温暖回应儿童的需求时，安全依恋就会发展。损害安全依恋的因素包括父母心理健康问题、物质滥用和家庭暴力。",
  328, [["Who developed attachment theory?","Sigmund Freud and Carl Jung","John Bowlby and Mary Ainsworth","B.F. Skinner and Ivan Pavlov","Jean Piaget and Lev Vygotsky","B","文章指出依恋理论由约翰·鲍尔比和玛丽·安斯沃思发展。"],["How many primary attachment styles did Ainsworth identify?","Two","Three","Five","Seven","B","文章指出安斯沃思确定了三种主要依恋风格。"],["What do securely attached children do when their caregiver is present?","Cry constantly","Explore confidently","Avoid the caregiver","Show no emotion","B","文章指出安全型依恋的儿童在照顾者在场时自信地探索。"],["Are attachment styles deterministic?","Yes, they never change","No, experiences in later relationships can modify internal working models","Only for men","Only during childhood","B","文章指出依恋风格不是决定性的，后期关系中的经验可以修改内在工作模型。"]]],
  [159, "The Psychology of Happiness", "心理", 1, "The pursuit of happiness is a universal human aspiration, yet understanding what truly contributes to well-being has proven more complex than simply accumulating pleasurable experiences. Positive psychology, pioneered by Martin Seligman, has shifted research focus from mental illness to understanding human flourishing.\n\nResearch reveals several consistent findings about happiness. Strong social relationships are the strongest predictor of life satisfaction across cultures. People who report having close friends and supportive family members are significantly happier than those who are socially isolated. The quality of relationships matters more than quantity.\n\nThe relationship between money and happiness is nuanced. Below a threshold that covers basic needs, increases in income do correlate with greater well-being. However, beyond this point, additional income produces diminishing returns. The hedonic treadmill describes how people quickly adapt to improvements in circumstances, returning to a baseline level of happiness. Lottery winners, after an initial surge of joy, typically return to their pre-win happiness levels within a year.\n\nSeveral practices have been shown to increase happiness. Expressing gratitude regularly, engaging in meaningful activities, helping others, exercising, and practicing mindfulness all contribute to well-being. Pursuing intrinsic goals related to personal growth, relationships, and community contribution produces more lasting satisfaction than extrinsic goals focused on wealth, fame, and appearance. Happiness is not a destination but a practice, cultivated through intentional habits and perspectives.",
  "追求幸福是全人类的普遍愿望，但理解什么真正有助于幸福比简单积累愉快体验更复杂。由马丁·塞利格曼开创的积极心理学将研究重点从心理疾病转向理解人类繁荣。\n\n研究揭示了关于幸福的几个一致发现。强大的社会关系是跨文化生活满意度最强的预测因子。报告有亲密朋友和支持性家庭成员的人比社交孤立的人明显更幸福。\n\n金钱与幸福之间的关系是微妙的。在覆盖基本需求的阈值以下，收入增加确实与更大幸福相关。然而超过这一点，额外收入产生递减的回报。享乐跑步机描述了人们如何快速适应环境改善，回到幸福基线水平。\n\n几种做法已被证明可以增加幸福。定期表达感恩、参与有意义的活动、帮助他人、锻炼和练习正念都有助于幸福。追求与个人成长、关系和社区贡献相关的内在目标比专注于财富、名望和外貌的外在目标产生更持久的满足感。",
  330, [["What is the strongest predictor of life satisfaction across cultures?","Wealth","Strong social relationships","Education level","Physical attractiveness","B","文章指出强大的社会关系是跨文化生活满意度最强的预测因子。"],["What does the hedonic treadmill describe?","A piece of exercise equipment","How people quickly adapt to improvements and return to baseline happiness","A type of therapy","An economic theory","B","文章指出享乐跑步机描述了人们如何快速适应环境改善，回到幸福基线水平。"],["How long do lottery winners typically return to pre-win happiness levels?","Within a week","Within a month","Within a year","Never","C","文章指出彩票中奖者通常在一年内回到中奖前的幸福水平。"],["What type of goals produce more lasting satisfaction?","Extrinsic goals focused on wealth","Intrinsic goals related to personal growth, relationships, and community contribution","Goals focused on fame","Goals focused on physical appearance","B","文章指出追求内在目标比外在目标产生更持久的满足感。"]]],
  [160, "Memory and How It Works", "心理", 2, "Memory is the process by which information is encoded, stored, and retrieved. It is essential for learning, reasoning, and virtually every aspect of cognitive function. Understanding how memory works and why it sometimes fails reveals the remarkable yet fallible nature of human cognition.\n\nMemory involves three stages: encoding, storage, and retrieval. Encoding transforms sensory input into a form that can be stored. Deep encoding, which involves meaningful processing of information, produces stronger memories than shallow encoding based on superficial features. Storage maintains encoded information over time. Retrieval accesses stored information when needed.\n\nShort-term memory holds approximately seven items for about twenty seconds. Rehearsal can maintain information in short-term memory indefinitely, but without it, information decays rapidly. Long-term memory has a virtually unlimited capacity and can last a lifetime. The transfer of information from short-term to long-term memory depends on factors including attention, emotional significance, and repetition.\n\nMemory failures occur for various reasons. Interference from similar memories can make retrieval difficult. Retrieval failures, commonly experienced as tip-of-the-tongue phenomena, occur when stored information cannot be accessed. False memories, which are recollections of events that never occurred or are distorted, demonstrate that memory is reconstructive rather than reproductive. Elizabeth Loftus's research has shown that post-event information, leading questions, and suggestion can profoundly alter memories, with important implications for legal testimony.",
  "记忆是信息编码、存储和检索的过程。它对学习、推理和几乎所有认知功能都至关重要。理解记忆如何运作以及为什么会失败揭示了人类认知的显著但不完美的本质。\n\n记忆涉及三个阶段：编码、存储和检索。编码将感官输入转化为可存储的形式。深度编码比浅层编码产生更强的记忆。存储随时间维持编码的信息。检索在需要时访问存储的信息。\n\n短期记忆可容纳约七个项目约二十秒。长期记忆具有几乎无限的容量，可以持续一生。从短期记忆到长期记忆的信息转移取决于注意力、情感意义和重复等因素。\n\n记忆失败有各种原因。来自相似记忆的干扰可使检索困难。虚假记忆证明记忆是重建性的而非复制性的。伊丽莎白·洛夫特斯的研究表明，事后信息、诱导性问题和暗示可以深刻改变记忆。",
  326, [["How many items can short-term memory typically hold?","About three","About seven","About twenty","About fifty","B","文章指出短期记忆可容纳约七个项目。"],["What produces stronger memories?","Shallow encoding based on superficial features","Deep encoding involving meaningful processing of information","Reading information only once","Ignoring the information","B","文章指出深度编码比浅层编码产生更强的记忆。"],["What is a false memory?","A memory that is perfectly accurate","A recollection of an event that never occurred or is distorted","A memory from childhood only","A memory that is only stored for a short time","B","文章指出虚假记忆是对从未发生的事件的回忆或扭曲的回忆。"],["Whose research showed that post-event information can alter memories?","Sigmund Freud's","B.F. Skinner's","Elizabeth Loftus's","Jean Piaget's","C","文章指出伊丽莎白·洛夫特斯的研究表明事后信息可以深刻改变记忆。"]]],
  [161, "The Psychology of Prejudice", "心理", 2, "Prejudice, a negative attitude toward members of a group based solely on their group membership, remains one of psychology's most important areas of study. Understanding the psychological mechanisms that produce and maintain prejudice is essential for developing effective strategies to reduce discrimination.\n\nSocial identity theory, proposed by Henri Tajfel, explains prejudice through the human tendency to categorize people into in-groups and out-groups. People derive self-esteem from their group memberships and favor their in-group while often denigrating out-groups. Even arbitrary and minimal group distinctions can produce in-group favoritism, demonstrating how easily prejudice can arise.\n\nStereotypes are cognitive shortcuts that simplify social perception but often lead to errors. When stereotypes are activated, they can influence perception, judgment, and behavior without conscious awareness. Implicit bias, measured through tests such as the Implicit Association Test, reveals that many people hold unconscious prejudices that contradict their explicitly stated beliefs.\n\nReducing prejudice requires sustained effort at multiple levels. Intergroup contact, particularly when it involves equal status, common goals, and cooperation, can reduce prejudice. Perspective-taking exercises, education about stereotyping processes, and exposure to counter-stereotypical examples all help. Legal and institutional measures that prohibit discrimination are necessary but insufficient without changes in individual attitudes and social norms.",
  "偏见是仅基于群体成员身份对群体成员的负面态度，仍然是心理学最重要的研究领域之一。理解产生和维持偏见的心理机制对于制定减少歧视的有效策略至关重要。\n\n由亨利·泰弗尔提出的社会认同理论通过人类将人分为内群体和外群体的倾向来解释偏见。人们从群体成员身份中获得自尊，偏袒自己的内群体而经常贬低外群体。即使是任意和最小的群体区分也能产生内群体偏爱。\n\n刻板印象是简化社会感知的认知捷径，但经常导致错误。内隐偏见揭示许多人持有与自己明确陈述的信念相矛盾的无意识偏见。\n\n减少偏见需要在多个层面持续努力。群体间接触，特别是涉及平等地位、共同目标和合作的接触，可以减少偏见。法律和机构措施是必要的，但如果没有个人态度和社会规范的改变是不够的。",
  322, [["What theory explains prejudice through in-group and out-group categorization?","Cognitive dissonance theory","Social identity theory proposed by Henri Tajfel","Maslow's hierarchy of needs","Classical conditioning","B","文章指出由亨利·泰弗尔提出的社会认同理论通过内外群体分类来解释偏见。"],["What are stereotypes?","Accurate descriptions of all group members","Cognitive shortcuts that simplify social perception but often lead to errors","Legal definitions of group rights","Physical characteristics of groups","B","文章指出刻板印象是简化社会感知的认知捷径，但经常导致错误。"],["What does implicit bias reveal?","That people never hold prejudices","That many people hold unconscious prejudices contradicting their stated beliefs","That prejudice is always intentional","That only uneducated people are prejudiced","B","文章指出内隐偏见揭示许多人持有与自己明确陈述的信念相矛盾的无意识偏见。"],["What conditions make intergroup contact most effective at reducing prejudice?","When groups compete against each other","When it involves equal status, common goals, and cooperation","When groups are kept completely separate","When one group is clearly superior","B","文章指出涉及平等地位、共同目标和合作的群体间接触可以减少偏见。"]]],
  [162, "Emotional Intelligence", "心理", 1, "Emotional intelligence, a concept popularized by psychologist Daniel Goleman, refers to the ability to recognize, understand, manage, and effectively use emotions in oneself and others. Research suggests that emotional intelligence may be as important as cognitive ability for success in personal and professional life.\n\nGoleman identified five components of emotional intelligence. Self-awareness involves recognizing one's own emotions and their effects. Self-regulation is the ability to control disruptive emotions and impulses. Motivation refers to the drive to achieve for internal reasons beyond money or status. Empathy is understanding others' emotions and perspectives. Social skills involve managing relationships and building networks.\n\nPeople with high emotional intelligence tend to navigate social situations more effectively. They communicate more clearly, resolve conflicts constructively, and build stronger relationships. In the workplace, emotionally intelligent leaders inspire trust, manage teams effectively, and create positive organizational cultures. Studies have found that emotional intelligence accounts for a significant portion of the variance in leadership effectiveness.\n\nUnlike IQ, which is relatively fixed throughout life, emotional intelligence can be developed with practice and effort. Strategies for improving emotional intelligence include mindfulness meditation to increase self-awareness, actively seeking feedback about how one's behavior affects others, practicing active listening, and learning to pause before reacting to emotional triggers. Developing emotional intelligence is a lifelong process that yields benefits across all domains of life.",
  "情商由心理学家丹尼尔·戈尔曼推广，指识别、理解、管理和有效使用自己和他人情绪的能力。研究表明，情商对于个人和职业生活的成功可能和认知能力一样重要。\n\n戈尔曼确定了情商的五个组成部分。自我意识涉及认识自己的情绪及其影响。自我调节是控制破坏性情绪和冲动的能力。动机指超越金钱或地位的内在成就驱动。共情是理解他人的情绪和观点。社交技能涉及管理关系和建立网络。\n\n高情商的人往往能更有效地处理社交场合。在工作场所，高情商的领导者激发信任，有效管理团队。研究发现情商在领导效能差异中占显著比例。\n\n与智商不同，情商可以通过练习和努力发展。改善情商的策略包括正念冥想以增加自我意识、积极寻求反馈、练习积极倾听和学习在反应情绪触发点之前暂停。",
  328, [["Who popularized the concept of emotional intelligence?","Sigmund Freud","Daniel Goleman","Albert Einstein","Carl Rogers","B","文章指出情商概念由丹尼尔·戈尔曼推广。"],["How many components of emotional intelligence did Goleman identify?","Three","Five","Seven","Ten","B","文章指出戈尔曼确定了情商的五个组成部分。"],["How does emotional intelligence differ from IQ?","It cannot be measured","It is relatively fixed like IQ","It can be developed with practice and effort unlike IQ","It is only important for children","C","文章指出与智商不同，情商可以通过练习和努力发展。"],["What is self-regulation in emotional intelligence?","Ignoring all emotions","The ability to control disruptive emotions and impulses","Expressing every emotion immediately","Suppressing emotions permanently","B","文章指出自我调节是控制破坏性情绪和冲动的能力。"]]],
  [163, "The Science of Sleep and Dreams", "心理", 2, "Sleep and dreams have fascinated humans for millennia, but only in recent decades has science begun to understand their functions. Sleep is not merely a period of inactivity but an active state essential for physical restoration, memory consolidation, and emotional regulation.\n\nSleep occurs in cycles lasting approximately 90 minutes, each consisting of distinct stages. Non-REM sleep progresses from light sleep through deep sleep, during which the body repairs tissues and the immune system is strengthened. REM sleep, characterized by rapid eye movements and vivid dreaming, plays crucial roles in memory consolidation, emotional processing, and creative problem-solving.\n\nDreams remain one of psychology's great mysteries. Freud viewed dreams as the royal road to the unconscious, representing repressed wishes in symbolic form. Modern neuroscience suggests that dreams result from the brain's attempt to make sense of random neural activity during REM sleep. However, this activation-synthesis theory does not fully explain why dreams often incorporate recent experiences and emotional concerns.\n\nResearch has revealed that dreams serve important functions. They help process emotional experiences, integrating difficult events into existing memory structures. They facilitate creative insights, with numerous scientific and artistic breakthroughs attributed to dream content. Lucid dreaming, in which dreamers become aware they are dreaming and can sometimes control dream content, offers researchers a unique window into consciousness. Understanding sleep and dreams remains an active frontier in psychological science.",
  "睡眠和梦境数千年来一直吸引着人类，但直到最近几十年科学才开始理解它们的功能。睡眠不是简单的不活动期，而是对身体恢复、记忆巩固和情绪调节至关重要的活跃状态。\n\n睡眠以约90分钟的周期发生。非REM睡眠从浅睡到深睡，在此期间身体修复组织，免疫系统得到加强。REM睡眠以快速眼动和生动梦境为特征，在记忆巩固、情绪处理和创造性问题解决中起关键作用。\n\n梦境仍然是心理学的伟大谜团之一。弗洛伊德将梦境视为通往潜意识的皇家大道。现代神经科学表明梦境可能是大脑试图理解REM睡眠期间随机神经活动的结果。\n\n研究揭示梦境具有重要功能。它们帮助处理情感体验，将困难事件整合到现有记忆结构中。它们促进创造性洞察。清醒梦为研究人员提供了研究意识的独特窗口。",
  326, [["How long does a typical sleep cycle last?","About 30 minutes","About 60 minutes","About 90 minutes","About 120 minutes","C","文章指出睡眠周期持续约90分钟。"],["What did Freud view dreams as?","Random neural activity","The royal road to the unconscious representing repressed wishes","Meaningless brain noise","Predictions of the future","B","文章指出弗洛伊德将梦境视为通往潜意识的皇家大道，以象征形式代表被压抑的愿望。"],["What is lucid dreaming?","Sleepwalking","When dreamers become aware they are dreaming and can sometimes control dream content","Having nightmares repeatedly","Not dreaming at all","B","文章指出清醒梦是梦者意识到自己在做梦并有时能控制梦境内容。"],["What role does REM sleep play?","Only physical repair","Memory consolidation, emotional processing, and creative problem-solving","Only muscle growth","Only body temperature regulation","B","文章指出REM睡眠在记忆巩固、情绪处理和创造性问题解决中起关键作用。"]]],
  [164, "Cognitive Dissonance", "心理", 2, "Cognitive dissonance, a concept introduced by Leon Festinger in 1957, refers to the mental discomfort experienced when holding two or more contradictory beliefs, values, or attitudes, or when behavior conflicts with beliefs. This discomfort motivates people to reduce the inconsistency, often by changing their attitudes or rationalizing their behavior.\n\nFestinger's classic study involved a doomsday cult whose predicted apocalypse failed to materialize. Rather than abandoning their beliefs, members increased their proselytizing, convincing themselves that their faith had saved the world. This demonstrates how people prefer to alter their perceptions rather than accept contradictory evidence.\n\nIn everyday life, cognitive dissonance operates constantly. A person who knows smoking is harmful but continues to smoke may convince themselves that the health risks are exaggerated. Someone who purchases an expensive item may seek information confirming it was worth the price while avoiding negative reviews. These rationalizations reduce discomfort but prevent honest self-assessment.\n\nUnderstanding cognitive dissonance has practical applications. Recognizing when dissonance is driving our thinking allows more rational decision-making. In education, creating moderate dissonance by presenting evidence that challenges existing beliefs can promote learning. In health behavior change, making people aware of contradictions between their values and actions can motivate positive change. The key is to tolerate the discomfort of inconsistency long enough to change behavior rather than merely rationalizing it away.",
  "认知失调是莱昂·费斯廷格于1957年提出的概念，指持有两个或多个矛盾信念、价值观或态度，或行为与信念冲突时体验到的心理不适。这种不适激励人们减少不一致。\n\n费斯廷格的经典研究涉及一个末日邪教，其预言的世界末日没有出现。成员们没有放弃他们的信念，反而加强了传教活动。这表明人们更愿意改变他们的认知而非接受矛盾证据。\n\n在日常生活中，认知失调不断运作。一个知道吸烟有害但继续吸烟的人可能说服自己健康风险被夸大了。某人购买了昂贵物品后可能寻找确认其物有所值的信息。\n\n理解认知失调有实际应用。认识到失调何时驱动我们的思维允许更理性的决策。关键是要容忍不一致的不适足够长时间以改变行为，而不是仅仅将其合理化掉。",
  328, [["Who introduced the concept of cognitive dissonance?","Sigmund Freud","Leon Festinger","B.F. Skinner","Carl Rogers","B","文章指出认知失调是莱昂·费斯廷格于1957年提出的概念。"],["What did members of the doomsday cult do when their prophecy failed?","Abandoned their beliefs completely","Increased their proselytizing and rationalized the failure","Admitted they were wrong","Started a new religion","B","文章指出成员们没有放弃信念，反而加强了传教活动。"],["How might a smoker reduce cognitive dissonance?","Quit smoking immediately","Convince themselves that the health risks are exaggerated","Seek negative information about smoking","Ignore all health information","B","文章指出吸烟者可能说服自己健康风险被夸大了。"],["What can creating moderate dissonance in education promote?","Student dropout","Learning by presenting evidence that challenges existing beliefs","Memorization only","Confusion only","B","文章指出在教育中，通过呈现挑战现有信念的证据来创造适度失调可以促进学习。"]]],
  [165, "The Psychology of Motivation", "心理", 1, "Motivation, the force that initiates, directs, and sustains behavior, is fundamental to understanding why people do what they do. Psychologists distinguish between intrinsic motivation, which comes from within, and extrinsic motivation, which comes from external rewards or punishments.\n\nIntrinsic motivation involves engaging in activities because they are inherently interesting or enjoyable. People who are intrinsically motivated read for pleasure, solve puzzles for the challenge, and create art for self-expression. Research consistently shows that intrinsic motivation produces higher quality work, greater creativity, and more persistent effort than extrinsic motivation.\n\nExtrinsic motivation involves engaging in activities to earn rewards or avoid punishments. While extrinsic motivators can be effective for routine tasks, they can undermine intrinsic motivation for tasks that are inherently interesting, a phenomenon known as the overjustification effect. When external rewards are introduced for activities people already enjoy, they may begin to see their behavior as driven by rewards rather than interest, reducing intrinsic motivation.\n\nSelf-determination theory, developed by Edward Deci and Richard Ryan, proposes that three basic psychological needs underlie intrinsic motivation: autonomy, the need to feel in control of one's behavior; competence, the need to feel effective and capable; and relatedness, the need to feel connected to others. Environments that support these needs foster intrinsic motivation, while those that undermine them through excessive control, negative feedback, or social isolation diminish it.",
  "动机是启动、指导和维持行为的力量，对理解人们为什么做他们所做的事至关重要。心理学家区分内在动机和外在动机。\n\n内在动机涉及参与活动是因为它们本身有趣或令人愉快。研究表明内在动机比外在动机产生更高质量的工作、更大的创造力和更持久的努力。\n\n外在动机涉及参与活动以获得奖励或避免惩罚。虽然外在激励对常规任务有效，但它们可能削弱本身有趣任务的内在动机，这一现象称为过度理由效应。\n\n由爱德华·德西和理查德·瑞安发展的自我决定理论提出，三种基本心理需求构成内在动机的基础：自主需求、胜任需求和关系需求。支持这些需求的环境培养内在动机。",
  326, [["What is intrinsic motivation?","Motivation from external rewards","Motivation that comes from within, engaging in activities because they are inherently interesting","Motivation from fear","Motivation from social pressure","B","文章指出内在动机涉及参与活动是因为它们本身有趣或令人愉快。"],["What is the overjustification effect?","When people are never motivated","When external rewards undermine intrinsic motivation for inherently interesting activities","When intrinsic motivation always increases","When people justify their bad behavior","B","文章指出过度理由效应是指外在奖励可能削弱本身有趣任务的内在动机。"],["What are the three basic psychological needs in self-determination theory?","Food, water, and shelter","Autonomy, competence, and relatedness","Money, power, and fame","Health, wealth, and intelligence","B","文章指出三种基本心理需求是自主、胜任和关系。"],["What does extrinsic motivation produce better results for?","Creative tasks","Routine tasks","Artistic expression","Personal growth","B","文章指出外在激励对常规任务有效。"]]],
  [166, "Social Influence and Conformity", "心理", 2, "Social influence, the ways in which people are affected by the real or imagined presence of others, is one of the most studied phenomena in social psychology. Understanding conformity, compliance, and obedience reveals the powerful forces that shape human behavior in group contexts.\n\nSolomon Asch's conformity experiments demonstrated the surprising power of social pressure. Participants asked to judge line lengths conformed to an obviously incorrect majority answer approximately one-third of the time. Even though the correct answer was clear, many participants went along with the group rather than risk social disapproval. However, the presence of just one other dissenter dramatically reduced conformity rates.\n\nStanley Milgram's obedience studies produced even more disturbing results. When instructed by an authority figure to administer increasingly powerful electric shocks to another person, approximately 65 percent of participants continued to the maximum voltage despite the victim's apparent distress. This demonstrated that ordinary people can commit harmful acts when instructed by perceived authority.\n\nThese findings have profound implications. They help explain phenomena ranging from the behavior of soldiers following orders to the spread of harmful social norms. Resistance to harmful social influence requires awareness of these pressures, critical evaluation of authority legitimacy, and the courage to stand against the group. Education about social influence processes can empower individuals to make more autonomous decisions.",
  "社会影响是人们受他人真实或想象存在影响的方式，是社会心理学中研究最多的现象之一。理解从众、顺从和服从揭示了在群体环境中塑造人类行为的强大力量。\n\n所罗门·阿希的从众实验展示了社会压力的惊人力量。参与者被要求判断线段长度时，约三分之一的时间顺从了明显不正确的多数答案。即使正确答案很清楚，许多参与者还是随大流。然而，只要有一个异议者就能大幅降低从众率。\n\n斯坦利·米尔格拉姆的服从研究产生了更令人不安的结果。当被权威人物指示向另一个人施加越来越强的电击时，约65%的参与者继续到最大电压。这表明普通人在被感知的权威指示时可能做出有害行为。\n\n这些发现具有深远影响。它们有助于解释从士兵服从命令到有害社会规范传播的现象。抵制有害社会影响需要意识到这些压力、批判性评估权威合法性以及反对群体的勇气。",
  330, [["In Asch's experiments, how often did participants conform to the incorrect majority?","About 10% of the time","About one-third of the time","About two-thirds of the time","About 90% of the time","B","文章指出参与者约三分之一的时间顺从了不正确的多数答案。"],["What percentage of participants continued to the maximum voltage in Milgram's studies?","About 10%","About 35%","About 65%","About 90%","C","文章指出约65%的参与者继续到最大电压。"],["What dramatically reduced conformity rates in Asch's experiments?","Paying participants more money","The presence of just one other dissenter","Making the task harder","Having a larger majority","B","文章指出只要有一个异议者就能大幅降低从众率。"],["What does resistance to harmful social influence require?","Blindly following authority","Awareness of pressures, critical evaluation of authority, and courage to stand against the group","Always agreeing with the majority","Avoiding all social situations","B","文章指出抵制有害社会影响需要意识到压力、批判性评估权威和反对群体的勇气。"]]],
  [167, "Personality and Trait Theory", "心理", 1, "Personality psychology seeks to understand the characteristic patterns of thoughts, feelings, and behaviors that make individuals unique. Among the major approaches to studying personality, trait theory has become the most influential framework in contemporary research.\n\nThe Big Five model, also known as the Five Factor Model, identifies five broad dimensions of personality. Openness to Experience reflects curiosity, creativity, and willingness to try new things. Conscientiousness involves organization, responsibility, and self-discipline. Extraversion encompasses sociability, assertiveness, and positive emotionality. Agreeableness includes cooperation, trust, and compassion. Neuroticism involves emotional instability, anxiety, and moodiness.\n\nThese five factors have been replicated across cultures, age groups, and measurement methods, suggesting they capture fundamental aspects of human personality. Each dimension exists on a continuum rather than as a category, meaning that people vary in degree rather than kind. Research has linked Big Five traits to important life outcomes including health, relationship satisfaction, career success, and longevity.\n\nPersonality traits have both genetic and environmental origins. Twin studies suggest that approximately 40 to 60 percent of the variance in personality traits is attributable to genetics. While core personality traits are relatively stable in adulthood, they are not completely fixed. Significant life events, sustained effort, and therapeutic interventions can produce meaningful changes in personality over time.",
  "人格心理学试图理解使个体独特的思想、情感和行为特征模式。在研究人格的主要方法中，特质理论已成为当代研究中最具影响力的框架。\n\n大五模型，也称为五因素模型，确定了人格的五个广泛维度。经验开放性反映好奇心和创造力。尽责性涉及组织性、责任感和自律。外向性包括社交性和果断性。宜人性包括合作、信任和同情。神经质涉及情绪不稳定和焦虑。\n\n这五个因素已在跨文化、年龄组和测量方法中得到复制。每个维度存在于连续体上而非类别中。研究将大五特质与重要生活结果联系起来，包括健康、关系满意度和职业成功。\n\n人格特质有遗传和环境两个来源。双胞胎研究表明人格特质变异的约40%至60%可归因于遗传。虽然核心人格特质在成年期相对稳定，但并非完全固定。",
  322, [["How many dimensions does the Big Five model identify?","Three","Five","Seven","Ten","B","文章指出大五模型确定了人格的五个广泛维度。"],["What does Conscientiousness involve?","Sociability and assertiveness","Organization, responsibility, and self-discipline","Cooperation and trust","Emotional instability","B","文章指出尽责性涉及组织性、责任感和自律。"],["What percentage of personality trait variance is attributable to genetics?","About 10 to 20 percent","About 40 to 60 percent","About 80 to 90 percent","About 100 percent","B","文章指出双胞胎研究表明约40%至60%的人格特质变异可归因于遗传。"],["Are personality traits completely fixed in adulthood?","Yes, they never change","No, significant life events, effort, and therapy can produce meaningful changes","Only extraversion can change","Only neuroticism can change","B","文章指出重大生活事件、持续努力和治疗干预可以随时间产生有意义的人格变化。"]]],
  [168, "The Psychology of Addiction", "心理", 2, "Addiction is a complex condition characterized by compulsive engagement in rewarding stimuli despite adverse consequences. While commonly associated with substance abuse, addiction also occurs with behaviors such as gambling, gaming, and internet use. Understanding the psychological mechanisms of addiction is essential for developing effective treatments.\n\nThe reward system plays a central role in addiction. Activities that are essential for survival, such as eating and social bonding, naturally activate the brain's reward circuitry, releasing dopamine and producing pleasure. Addictive substances and behaviors hijack this system, producing dopamine releases far exceeding natural rewards. Repeated exposure leads to tolerance, requiring more of the substance or behavior to achieve the same effect.\n\nThe cycle of addiction involves three phases. The binge phase is characterized by compulsive use. The withdrawal phase produces negative emotional states when the substance or behavior is unavailable. The preoccupation phase involves anticipating and craving the next use. This cycle becomes increasingly entrenched as the brain adapts to repeated stimulation.\n\nTreatment approaches have evolved from viewing addiction as moral failure to understanding it as a brain disorder. Cognitive behavioral therapy helps individuals identify triggers and develop coping strategies. Motivational interviewing resolves ambivalence about change. Contingency management provides tangible rewards for positive behaviors. For substance addictions, medication-assisted treatment reduces cravings and withdrawal symptoms. Recovery is typically a long-term process, with relapse being a common part of the journey rather than a sign of failure.",
  "成瘾是一种以尽管有不良后果仍强迫性参与奖赏刺激为特征的复杂状况。虽然通常与物质滥用相关，但成瘾也发生在赌博、游戏和互联网使用等行为中。理解成瘾的心理机制对于制定有效治疗至关重要。\n\n奖赏系统在成瘾中起着核心作用。对生存至关重要的活动自然激活大脑的奖赏回路，释放多巴胺并产生快感。成瘾物质和行为劫持了这一系统，产生远超自然奖赏的多巴胺释放。反复暴露导致耐受性。\n\n成瘾周期涉及三个阶段：暴食期以强迫使用为特征；戒断期在物质或行为不可用时产生负面情绪状态；专注期涉及预期和渴望下次使用。\n\n治疗方法已从将成瘾视为道德失败演变为将其理解为脑部疾病。认知行为疗法帮助个体识别触发因素并发展应对策略。康复通常是一个长期过程，复发是旅程中的常见部分而非失败的标志。",
  330, [["What do addictive substances do to the brain's reward system?","They have no effect","They hijack the system, producing dopamine releases far exceeding natural rewards","They reduce dopamine permanently","They only affect serotonin","B","文章指出成瘾物质和行为劫持了奖赏系统，产生远超自然奖赏的多巴胺释放。"],["What are the three phases of the addiction cycle?","Planning, executing, and reviewing","Binge, withdrawal, and preoccupation","Denial, anger, and acceptance","Introduction, development, and conclusion","B","文章指出成瘾周期涉及暴食期、戒断期和专注期三个阶段。"],["What does tolerance in addiction mean?","Becoming allergic to the substance","Needing more of the substance or behavior to achieve the same effect","Enjoying the substance less over time","Only needing a small amount","B","文章指出反复暴露导致耐受性，需要更多的物质或行为才能达到相同效果。"],["How is relapse viewed in modern addiction treatment?","As a sign of complete failure","As a common part of the recovery journey rather than a sign of failure","As something that never happens","As a reason to give up treatment","B","文章指出复发是旅程中的常见部分而非失败的标志。"]]],
  [169, "The Theory of Multiple Intelligences", "心理", 1, "Howard Gardner's theory of multiple intelligences, proposed in 1983, challenged the traditional view of intelligence as a single, general ability measured by IQ tests. Instead, Gardner proposed that humans possess several distinct intelligences, each representing a different way of processing information.\n\nGardner originally identified seven intelligences. Linguistic intelligence involves sensitivity to spoken and written language. Logical-mathematical intelligence concerns capacity for deductive reasoning and detecting patterns. Spatial intelligence includes the ability to visualize and manipulate objects in space. Musical intelligence involves skill in performance and appreciation of musical patterns. Bodily-kinesthetic intelligence is the ability to use the body effectively. Interpersonal intelligence involves understanding others' moods and motivations. Intrapersonal intelligence is the capacity to understand oneself.\n\nGardner later added naturalistic intelligence, the ability to recognize and classify natural patterns, and considered existential intelligence, the capacity to ponder deep questions about human existence. Each person possesses a unique profile of intelligences, with some areas stronger than others.\n\nThe theory has significant educational implications. It suggests that teaching should address multiple intelligences rather than focusing exclusively on linguistic and logical-mathematical abilities. However, the theory has faced criticism. Some psychologists argue that the proposed intelligences are better understood as talents or skills rather than distinct forms of intelligence, and that a general intelligence factor better explains cognitive performance. Despite these debates, the theory has encouraged more diverse and inclusive approaches to education.",
  "霍华德·加德纳于1983年提出的多元智能理论挑战了将智力视为可通过IQ测试衡量的单一一般能力的传统观点。相反，加德纳提出人类拥有几种不同的智能，每种代表不同的信息处理方式。\n\n加德纳最初确定了七种智能。语言智能涉及对口头和书面语言的敏感性。逻辑数学智能涉及演绎推理和模式检测的能力。空间智能包括可视化和操作空间物体的能力。音乐智能涉及表演和欣赏音乐模式的技能。身体动觉智能是有效使用身体的能力。人际智能涉及理解他人的情绪和动机。内省智能是理解自己的能力。\n\n加德纳后来增加了自然智能，考虑了存在智能。每个人都拥有独特的智能组合。\n\n该理论有重要的教育意义。它表明教学应该解决多种智能，而不是仅仅专注于语言和逻辑数学能力。然而该理论也面临批评。尽管存在争论，该理论鼓励了更多样化和包容性的教育方法。",
  330, [["When did Gardner propose the theory of multiple intelligences?","1963","1973","1983","1993","C","文章指出加德纳于1983年提出多元智能理论。"],["How many intelligences did Gardner originally identify?","Five","Seven","Nine","Twelve","B","文章指出加德纳最初确定了七种智能。"],["What is interpersonal intelligence?","The ability to solve math problems","Understanding others' moods and motivations","The ability to run fast","The ability to write poetry","B","文章指出人际智能涉及理解他人的情绪和动机。"],["What criticism has the theory faced?","That it has too few intelligences","That the proposed intelligences are better understood as talents or skills rather than distinct forms of intelligence","That Gardner was not a real psychologist","That IQ tests are always accurate","B","文章指出一些心理学家认为所提出的智能更适合理解为才能或技能而非不同的智力形式。"]]],
  [170, "The Psychology of Group Dynamics", "心理", 2, "Group dynamics, the study of how individuals behave in group settings, reveals that the presence of others can profoundly alter individual behavior. Understanding these dynamics has important implications for organizations, teams, and society.\n\nSocial facilitation occurs when the presence of others enhances performance on simple or well-learned tasks but impairs performance on complex or unfamiliar tasks. This dual effect explains why athletes often perform better before crowds while students may struggle with difficult problems when observed. The mere presence of others increases physiological arousal, which strengthens the dominant response.\n\nGroupthink, identified by Irving Janis, occurs when the desire for group harmony overrides realistic appraisal of alternatives. Cohesive groups under stress may suppress dissent, ignore outside information, and make disastrous decisions. Examples include the Bay of Pigs invasion and the Challenger space shuttle disaster. Preventing groupthink requires encouraging dissent, seeking outside perspectives, and having leaders avoid stating preferences before discussion.\n\nSocial loafing describes the tendency for individuals to exert less effort when working in a group than when working alone. When personal contributions cannot be identified, some group members reduce their effort, relying on others to carry the load. Strategies to combat social loafing include making individual contributions identifiable, increasing task importance, and building group cohesion where members value collective outcomes.",
  "群体动力学研究个体在群体环境中的行为方式，揭示了他人的存在可以深刻改变个体行为。理解这些动力学对组织、团队和社会具有重要意义。\n\n社会促进发生在他人存在时增强了简单或熟悉任务的表现，但损害了复杂或不熟悉任务的表现。这种双重效应解释了为什么运动员在观众面前往往表现更好，而学生在被观察时可能在难题上挣扎。\n\n由欧文·贾尼斯识别的群体思维发生在对群体和谐的渴望压倒对替代方案的现实评估时。凝聚力强的压力群体可能压制异议，忽略外部信息，做出灾难性决定。\n\n社会懈怠描述了个体在群体中工作比单独工作时付出更少努力的倾向。当个人贡献无法被识别时，一些群体成员会减少努力。对抗社会懈怠的策略包括使个人贡献可识别、增加任务重要性和建立群体凝聚力。",
  326, [["When does social facilitation impair performance?","On simple tasks","On complex or unfamiliar tasks","When working alone","Only in sports","B","文章指出他人存在损害了复杂或不熟悉任务的表现。"],["What is groupthink?","When groups always make good decisions","When the desire for group harmony overrides realistic appraisal of alternatives","When everyone in a group thinks independently","When groups compete against each other","B","文章指出群体思维发生在对群体和谐的渴望压倒对替代方案的现实评估时。"],["What is social loafing?","Working harder in groups","The tendency to exert less effort when working in a group than alone","A type of group exercise","Floating on water socially","B","文章指出社会懈怠是个体在群体中工作比单独工作时付出更少努力的倾向。"],["How can groupthink be prevented?","By having the leader state their preference first","By encouraging dissent, seeking outside perspectives, and having leaders avoid stating preferences early","By making the group larger","By eliminating all discussion","B","文章指出防止群体思维需要鼓励异议、寻求外部观点和领导者避免在讨论前陈述偏好。"]]],
  [171, "Resilience and Post-Traumatic Growth", "心理", 1, "Resilience is the ability to adapt and recover from adversity, trauma, or significant stress. Far from being a rare trait, research shows that resilience is common and can be developed throughout life. Understanding resilience challenges the assumption that trauma inevitably leads to lasting psychological damage.\n\nSeveral factors contribute to resilience. Supportive relationships provide emotional comfort, practical assistance, and models of coping. Optimism, the expectation that positive outcomes will occur, helps people maintain hope during difficult times. Cognitive flexibility allows people to reframe adverse experiences and find meaning in suffering. Self-efficacy, the belief in one's ability to influence outcomes, motivates active coping rather than passive resignation.\n\nPost-traumatic growth, a concept developed by Richard Tedeschi and Lawrence Calhoun, describes positive psychological changes that can result from struggling with highly challenging life circumstances. Many people who experience trauma report deeper relationships, greater personal strength, new possibilities, enhanced appreciation of life, and spiritual development. Post-traumatic growth does not mean that trauma is desirable but rather that humans can find meaning and strength in the aftermath of adversity.\n\nBuilding resilience involves developing healthy coping strategies, maintaining social connections, practicing self-care, and cultivating a growth mindset. Communities and institutions can foster resilience by providing social support, creating safe environments, and ensuring access to mental health resources. Understanding that resilience is a skill that can be developed offers hope to those facing life's inevitable challenges.",
  "心理韧性是从逆境、创伤或重大压力中适应和恢复的能力。研究表明心理韧性是常见的，可以在一生中发展。理解心理韧性挑战了创伤必然导致持久心理损害的假设。\n\n几个因素有助于心理韧性。支持性关系提供情感安慰和实际帮助。乐观帮助人们在困难时期保持希望。认知灵活性允许人们重新构建不利经历并在痛苦中找到意义。自我效能感激励积极应对而非被动顺从。\n\n创伤后成长是由理查德·泰德斯基和劳伦斯·卡尔霍恩发展的概念，描述了从与极具挑战性的生活环境斗争中产生的积极心理变化。许多经历创伤的人报告了更深层的关系、更大的个人力量和对生活的更高赞赏。\n\n培养心理韧性涉及发展健康的应对策略、维持社交联系和培养成长心态。社区和机构可以通过提供社会支持和确保获得心理健康资源来培养心理韧性。",
  330, [["Is resilience a rare trait?","Yes, only a few people have it","No, research shows resilience is common and can be developed","Only children can develop it","It is entirely genetic","B","文章指出研究表明心理韧性是常见的，可以在一生中发展。"],["What is post-traumatic growth?","Becoming physically stronger after injury","Positive psychological changes resulting from struggling with challenging life circumstances","Forgetting about trauma completely","Never experiencing stress again","B","文章指出创伤后成长描述了从与极具挑战性的生活环境斗争中产生的积极心理变化。"],["What does cognitive flexibility allow people to do?","Only think about one thing","Reframe adverse experiences and find meaning in suffering","Avoid all negative thoughts","Never change their opinions","B","文章指出认知灵活性允许人们重新构建不利经历并在痛苦中找到意义。"],["What is self-efficacy?","The belief in one's ability to influence outcomes","The ability to lift heavy weights","A type of medication","Social popularity","A","文章指出自我效能感是影响结果的信念，激励积极应对。"]]],
  [172, "The Power of Habit", "心理", 1, "Habits are automatic behaviors triggered by contextual cues, performed with minimal conscious thought. They form the backbone of daily life, with research suggesting that approximately 40 to 45 percent of daily behaviors are habitual rather than consciously chosen.\n\nThe habit loop, described by Charles Duhigg, consists of three components. The cue is the trigger that initiates the behavior, such as a time of day, emotional state, or location. The routine is the behavior itself. The reward is the benefit received, which reinforces the association between cue and routine. Over time, this loop becomes increasingly automatic as the brain encodes the association in neural pathways.\n\nHabits are difficult to change because they operate below conscious awareness and are deeply encoded in the basal ganglia. Willpower alone is generally insufficient for lasting habit change, as demonstrated by the high failure rate of New Year's resolutions. However, understanding the habit loop provides strategies for modification. One effective approach is to keep the cue and reward while changing the routine. For example, replacing the routine of snacking on junk food with taking a walk, while maintaining the same cue and reward structure.\n\nCreating new habits requires consistent repetition in stable contexts. Research suggests that it takes an average of 66 days for a new behavior to become automatic, though this varies widely from 18 to 254 days depending on the complexity of the behavior and individual differences. Starting with small, manageable changes and building gradually produces more sustainable results than attempting dramatic transformations.",
  "习惯是由情境线索触发、以最少的意识思考执行的自动行为。它们构成日常生活的支柱，研究表明大约40%至45%的日常行为是习惯性的而非有意识选择的。\n\n查尔斯·杜希格描述的习惯回路由三个组成部分构成。线索是触发行为的诱因。惯例是行为本身。奖赏是获得的益处，它强化了线索和惯例之间的关联。随着时间推移，这种回路变得越来越自动化。\n\n习惯很难改变，因为它们在意识意识之下运作，深深编码在基底神经节中。仅凭意志力通常不足以实现持久的习惯改变。然而，理解习惯回路提供了修改的策略。一种有效方法是保持线索和奖赏，同时改变惯例。\n\n创建新习惯需要在稳定的情境中持续重复。研究表明新行为变得自动化平均需要66天，尽管根据行为复杂性和个体差异，这一时间从18到254天不等。",
  330, [["What percentage of daily behaviors are habitual?","About 10 to 15 percent","About 40 to 45 percent","About 70 to 75 percent","About 90 to 95 percent","B","文章指出大约40%至45%的日常行为是习惯性的。"],["What are the three components of the habit loop?","Thinking, feeling, and acting","Cue, routine, and reward","Stimulus, response, and consequence","Beginning, middle, and end","B","文章指出习惯回路由线索、惯例和奖赏三个组成部分构成。"],["How long does it take on average for a new behavior to become automatic?","About 7 days","About 21 days","About 66 days","About 365 days","C","文章指出新行为变得自动化平均需要66天。"],["What is one effective approach to changing a habit?","Eliminate all cues","Keep the cue and reward while changing the routine","Use only willpower","Ignore the reward","B","文章指出一种有效方法是保持线索和奖赏，同时改变惯例。"]]],
  [173, "The Bystander Effect", "心理", 2, "The bystander effect refers to the phenomenon in which individuals are less likely to offer help to a victim when other people are present. This counterintuitive finding, one of the most replicated in social psychology, has important implications for understanding helping behavior in emergencies.\n\nThe effect was first systematically studied after the murder of Kitty Genovese in 1964, reportedly witnessed by 38 neighbors who failed to intervene or call police. While later investigations questioned the accuracy of this account, the incident inspired Bibb Latane and John Darley's groundbreaking research on bystander intervention.\n\nLatane and Darley identified several psychological processes that explain the bystander effect. Diffusion of responsibility means that each bystander assumes someone else will help, reducing the personal obligation felt by any individual. Pluralistic ignorance occurs when people look to others for cues about how to interpret a situation; if no one else seems alarmed, each person concludes the situation is not an emergency. Evaluation apprehension involves fear of being judged negatively for overreacting.\n\nThe bystander effect can be reduced through awareness and training. When people understand the phenomenon, they are more likely to take responsibility and act. Simple interventions, such as pointing to a specific person and asking them directly for help, overcome diffusion of responsibility. Organizations and communities that promote a culture of helping and provide clear protocols for emergencies can mitigate the bystander effect and save lives.",
  "旁观者效应是指当有其他人在场时，个体不太可能向受害者提供帮助的现象。这一违反直觉的发现在社会心理学中是最被重复验证的之一，对理解紧急情况下的帮助行为具有重要意义。\n\n该效应是在1964年基蒂·吉诺维斯谋杀案后首次系统研究的。虽然后来的调查质疑了这一叙述的准确性，但该事件激发了比布·拉塔内和约翰·达利关于旁观者干预的开创性研究。\n\n拉塔内和达利确定了几种解释旁观者效应的心理过程。责任分散意味着每个旁观者假设其他人会帮助，减少任何个体感受到的个人义务。多元无知发生在人们根据其他人的反应来判断情况时。评价担忧涉及害怕因过度反应而被负面评判。\n\n旁观者效应可以通过意识和培训来减少。当人们理解这一现象时，他们更有可能承担责任并采取行动。简单的干预，如指向特定的人并直接请求帮助，可以克服责任分散。",
  322, [["What is the bystander effect?","The tendency to help more when others are present","The phenomenon where individuals are less likely to help a victim when other people are present","The effect of being a good neighbor","The tendency to call police immediately","B","文章指出旁观者效应是指当有其他人在场时，个体不太可能向受害者提供帮助的现象。"],["What case inspired the systematic study of the bystander effect?","The Milgram experiment","The murder of Kitty Genovese in 1964","The Stanford prison experiment","The Asch conformity study","B","文章指出该效应是在1964年基蒂·吉诺维斯谋杀案后首次系统研究的。"],["What does diffusion of responsibility mean?","That everyone takes equal responsibility","That each bystander assumes someone else will help, reducing personal obligation","That no one is ever responsible","That only the police should help","B","文章指出责任分散意味着每个旁观者假设其他人会帮助，减少个人义务。"],["How can the bystander effect be reduced?","By having more bystanders","Through awareness, training, and directly asking specific people for help","By ignoring emergencies","By avoiding all social situations","B","文章指出旁观者效应可以通过意识、培训和直接向特定人员请求帮助来减少。"]]],
  [174, "The Stanford Prison Experiment", "心理", 2, "The Stanford Prison Experiment, conducted by Philip Zimbardo in 1971, is one of the most famous and controversial studies in psychology. College students were randomly assigned to play the roles of prisoners and guards in a simulated prison, but the experiment had to be terminated after just six days due to the extreme and disturbing behavior that emerged.\n\nThe guards, given uniforms, batons, and authority, quickly became abusive. They imposed arbitrary rules, subjected prisoners to humiliating treatment, and displayed sadistic behavior that escalated over time. The prisoners, stripped of their identities and referred to by numbers rather than names, became passive, depressed, and in some cases emotionally broken. Even Zimbardo himself, acting as the prison superintendent, became caught up in the role.\n\nThe experiment seemed to demonstrate the power of situational forces to overwhelm individual personality. Ordinary college students, when placed in positions of unchecked power or complete powerlessness, behaved in ways that would have been unimaginable in their normal lives. This finding challenged the dispositional view that bad behavior results from bad people, suggesting instead that powerful situations can make good people do bad things.\n\nHowever, the experiment has been heavily criticized. Questions have been raised about methodological flaws, including whether guards were coached to be harsh, whether demand characteristics influenced behavior, and whether the selection process attracted participants prone to aggression. Ethical concerns about the psychological harm inflicted on participants led to strengthened research protections. Despite its controversies, the Stanford Prison Experiment remains a powerful illustration of how institutional roles and situational pressures can shape behavior.",
  "1971年由菲利普·津巴多进行的斯坦福监狱实验是心理学中最著名和最具争议的研究之一。大学生被随机分配扮演囚犯和看守的角色，但由于出现了极端和令人不安的行为，实验在仅仅六天后不得不终止。\n\n看守们被赋予制服、警棍和权力后，很快变得虐待性。他们强加任意规则，使囚犯遭受侮辱性对待。囚犯们被剥夺身份，以编号而非姓名称呼，变得被动、沮丧。\n\n该实验似乎展示了情境力量压倒个人性格的力量。普通大学生在处于不受制约的权力或完全无力地位时，表现出正常生活中无法想象的行为方式。\n\n然而，该实验受到了严厉批评。关于方法论缺陷的问题包括看守是否被指导要严厉，以及选拔过程是否吸引了有攻击倾向的参与者。对参与者造成心理伤害的伦理担忧导致了研究保护的加强。尽管存在争议，斯坦福监狱实验仍然是制度角色和情境压力如何塑造行为的有力说明。",
  332, [["How long did the Stanford Prison Experiment last before being terminated?","One day","Three days","Six days","Two weeks","C","文章指出实验在仅仅六天后不得不终止。"],["What happened to the guards in the experiment?","They became kind and supportive","They quickly became abusive, imposing arbitrary rules and humiliating prisoners","They refused to participate","They tried to help the prisoners escape","B","文章指出看守们很快变得虐待性，强加任意规则，使囚犯遭受侮辱性对待。"],["What did the experiment seem to demonstrate?","That people are inherently evil","The power of situational forces to overwhelm individual personality","That prisoners always rebel","That college students are unethical","B","文章指出该实验似乎展示了情境力量压倒个人性格的力量。"],["What major concern led to strengthened research protections?","The cost of the experiment","Ethical concerns about psychological harm inflicted on participants","The experiment was too short","Too many participants wanted to join","B","文章指出对参与者造成心理伤害的伦理担忧导致了研究保护的加强。"]]],
  [175, "Learned Helplessness and Depression", "心理", 2, "Learned helplessness is a psychological phenomenon in which individuals exposed to uncontrollable aversive events come to believe that they have no ability to influence outcomes, even when opportunities for control become available. This concept, discovered by Martin Seligman through experiments with dogs, has profound implications for understanding depression and motivation.\n\nIn Seligman's experiments, dogs exposed to inescapable electric shocks later failed to escape when escape became possible, instead passively enduring the shocks. The dogs had learned that their actions made no difference, and this expectation of helplessness persisted even when conditions changed. This finding paralleled the symptoms of depression in humans, including passivity, loss of motivation, and feelings of hopelessness.\n\nThe attributional reformulation of learned helplessness, developed by Lyn Abramson, Martin Seligman, and John Teasdale, added crucial nuance. People's explanatory style determines whether helplessness becomes pervasive and chronic. Those who attribute negative events to internal, stable, and global causes are most vulnerable to depression. For example, attributing a failure to personal incompetence rather than to specific circumstances creates a pessimistic explanatory style that generalizes across situations.\n\nCognitive behavioral therapy effectively treats depression by challenging these pessimistic attributional patterns. By helping individuals recognize and reframe negative automatic thoughts, develop more balanced interpretations, and test their beliefs through behavioral experiments, therapy restores a sense of agency and control. Seligman's later work on learned optimism demonstrates that explanatory styles can be deliberately cultivated, offering a preventative approach to depression.",
  "习得性无助是一种心理现象，暴露于不可控厌恶事件的个体开始相信自己没有能力影响结果，即使控制机会变得可用时也是如此。这一概念由马丁·塞利格曼通过对狗的实验发现，对理解抑郁症和动机具有深远影响。\n\n在塞利格曼的实验中，暴露于不可逃避电击的狗后来在逃避成为可能时也未能逃脱。狗已经学会了它们的行为没有影响，这种无助的期望即使条件改变也持续存在。\n\n习得性无助的归因重新阐述增加了关键的细微差别。人们的解释风格决定了无助感是否变得普遍和慢性。那些将负面事件归因于内部、稳定和全局原因的人最容易患抑郁症。\n\n认知行为疗法通过挑战这些悲观的归因模式有效治疗抑郁症。塞利格曼后来关于习得乐观的研究表明，解释风格可以被有意识地培养，为抑郁症提供了一种预防性方法。",
  328, [["Who discovered learned helplessness?","Sigmund Freud","Martin Seligman","B.F. Skinner","Ivan Pavlov","B","文章指出习得性无助由马丁·塞利格曼发现。"],["What did Seligman's dogs do when escape became possible?","They escaped immediately","They failed to escape, passively enduring the shocks","They attacked the researcher","They became aggressive toward other dogs","B","文章指出暴露于不可逃避电击的狗后来在逃避成为可能时也未能逃脱。"],["What type of attributional style makes people most vulnerable to depression?","Attributing negative events to external, unstable, and specific causes","Attributing negative events to internal, stable, and global causes","Always blaming others","Never attributing events to any cause","B","文章指出将负面事件归因于内部、稳定和全局原因的人最容易患抑郁症。"],["What does cognitive behavioral therapy do for depression?","It prescribes medication only","It challenges pessimistic attributional patterns and helps develop more balanced interpretations","It tells patients to ignore their feelings","It focuses only on childhood experiences","B","文章指出认知行为疗法通过挑战悲观的归因模式有效治疗抑郁症。"]]],
  [176, "The Psychology of Creativity", "心理", 1, "Creativity, the ability to produce ideas that are both novel and useful, has been a subject of growing interest in psychology. Far from being a mysterious gift bestowed on a lucky few, creativity is increasingly understood as a cognitive process that can be nurtured and developed.\n\nThe creative process typically involves four stages. Preparation involves gathering information and defining the problem. Incubation is a period of unconscious processing where the mind works on the problem without deliberate attention. Illumination is the sudden appearance of a solution or insight, often called the eureka moment. Verification involves testing and refining the creative idea.\n\nSeveral factors influence creative output. Domain-relevant knowledge provides the raw material for creative combinations. Divergent thinking, the ability to generate multiple possible solutions, is a key cognitive skill. Intrinsic motivation, driven by interest and enjoyment rather than external rewards, consistently predicts creative achievement. Environmental factors including freedom, sufficient resources, and supportive colleagues also contribute.\n\nContrary to the myth of the tortured artist, creativity flourishes under conditions of psychological safety and positive affect. Research shows that people generate more creative ideas when they are in positive moods. However, creative work also requires discipline and persistence. Thomas Edison's observation that genius is one percent inspiration and ninety-nine percent perspiration captures this balance between insight and effort. The most creative individuals combine the ability to generate novel ideas with the discipline to develop and implement them.",
  "创造力是产生既新颖又有用的想法的能力，越来越引起心理学的关注。创造力越来越被理解为一种可以培养和发展的认知过程，而非神秘的天赋。\n\n创造过程通常涉及四个阶段。准备涉及收集信息和定义问题。酝酿是无意识处理的时期。启发是解决方案或洞察的突然出现。验证涉及测试和完善创意想法。\n\n几个因素影响创意产出。领域相关知识为创意组合提供原材料。发散思维是关键的认知技能。内在动机持续预测创造性成就。环境因素包括自由、充足资源和支持性同事也有贡献。\n\n与受苦艺术家的神话相反，创造力在心理安全和积极情绪的条件下蓬勃发展。然而创造性工作也需要纪律和坚持。爱迪生关于天才是百分之一灵感和百分之九十九汗水的观察捕捉了洞察与努力之间的平衡。",
  326, [["How many stages does the creative process typically involve?","Two","Three","Four","Six","C","文章指出创造过程通常涉及四个阶段。"],["What is divergent thinking?","Finding the single correct answer","The ability to generate multiple possible solutions","Thinking only about the past","Converging on one idea","B","文章指出发散思维是产生多种可能解决方案的能力。"],["Under what conditions does creativity flourish?","Under extreme stress and pressure","Under conditions of psychological safety and positive affect","Only in complete isolation","Only when working for money","B","文章指出创造力在心理安全和积极情绪的条件下蓬勃发展。"],["What type of motivation consistently predicts creative achievement?","Extrinsic motivation from rewards","Intrinsic motivation driven by interest and enjoyment","Motivation from fear of failure","Motivation from competition","B","文章指出内在动机持续预测创造性成就。"]]
]];
